  "text": "It is generally known that normal prostates produce protein materials such as PSA thanks to differentiated actions of androgen [CITATION_1] . Morgentaler [CITATION_2] suggested that testosterone values were low in hypogonadism patients and that the possibility of prostate cancer would be high if PSA values were 4.0 ng/ml or lower. Koo and Shim [CITATION_3] examined 120 patients with a PSA value of 10.0 ng/ml or higher who underwent a transrectal biopsy and reported that testosterone values at diagnosis were not associated with enhanced PSA values. In the present study, however, PSA values were higher in the group with low preoperative testosterone (10.45 ng/ml vs 7.67 ng/ml). This is considered to be because the number of subjects was small; thus, additional studies will be necessary.",
